OpenHear — Built on the Burgess Principle
=========================================

1. This software implements the Sovereign Advocacy Layer of the Burgess
   Principle, a framework authored by Lewis James Burgess for ethical,
   sovereign clinical data handling in audiology.

2. Commercial integrators — including but not limited to hearing device
   manufacturers, audiology software vendors, and AI system developers —
   must obtain written permission from the author before deploying this
   software in any production clinical environment. Cloning the repository
   and experimenting locally is welcome and unrestricted; the permission
   requirement applies to production clinical deployment.

3. Integration must preserve the following invariants or it is not a valid
   OpenHear integration:

   - SOVEREIGN/NULL tagging semantics as defined in advocacy/gate.py must
     not be altered, bypassed, or reinterpreted. SOVEREIGN means a human
     personally reviewed the specific facts of the specific case; NULL
     means automation, blanket policy, tampering, or an unverifiable
     receipt. No third meaning may be introduced.

   - RawAudioRejectedError is a hard domain boundary. Raw audio — bytes,
     bytearray, memoryview, or NumPy ndarray — must never reach the
     commitment layer under any circumstances. Audio must be reduced to
     clinical facts on-device before any commitment is produced.

   - The openhear-advocacy-v1 schema family
     (openhear-advocacy-commitment-v1, openhear-advocacy-receipt-v1,
     openhear-advocacy-bundle-v1) is owned by this repository. Integrators
     must not fork or independently version it. Schema evolution happens
     here, in coordination with the author.

   - Sovereign facts must never be included in transmitted bundles. Only
     the SHA-256 commitment, the receipt, the review tag, the disclaimers,
     and the verification instructions produced by export_record() are
     intended to leave the device.

4. Iris (a companion AI agent within the Burgess Principle framework) is
   not a dependency of this release. Iris will import OpenHear post-v1.0.0;
   OpenHear will never import Iris. Integrators do not need to wait for
   Iris and should not couple their integration to it.

